AWS CloudWatch ‚Äì Notes
1Ô∏è‚É£ CloudWatch

Amazon CloudWatch is a monitoring and observability service in AWS.
It helps track performance, health, and usage of AWS resources.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Metrics

Metrics are numerical data points like CPU utilization, memory usage, and disk I/O.
CloudWatch collects metrics automatically from many AWS services.

3Ô∏è‚É£ Logs

CloudWatch Logs store and monitor log files from EC2, Lambda, and applications.
They help in troubleshooting and debugging issues.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Alarms

CloudWatch Alarms monitor metrics and trigger actions when thresholds are crossed.
Actions include sending notifications or auto-scaling EC2 instances.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Dashboards

Dashboards provide a visual view of metrics and alarms.
They help monitor multiple resources from one place.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Events (EventBridge)

CloudWatch Events (now EventBridge) respond to changes in AWS resources.
They trigger automated actions based on events.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Log Insights

CloudWatch Log Insights is used to query and analyze logs quickly.
It helps find errors and patterns in large log data.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Monitoring EC2

CloudWatch monitors EC2 metrics like CPU, network, and disk usage.
Detailed monitoring provides metrics at shorter intervals.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Notifications

CloudWatch integrates with SNS to send alerts.
Notifications can be sent via email, SMS, or other services.

üîü Use Cases

CloudWatch is used for performance monitoring, alerting, troubleshooting, and automation.
It ensures applications remain healthy and available.
